  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some interesting startups of 2014?",
  "response": "2014 was a vibrant year for startups across various industries, with many companies emerging that have since grown into major players or been acquired. Here are some notable startups from 2014 that stood out for their innovation and potential:\n\n1. **Slack** - Originally a gaming company, Slack pivoted to become a messaging platform for teams. It quickly gained popularity for its ease of use and integration with other work tools.\n\n2. **Zenefits** - Zenefits offered a cloud-based software as a service (SaaS) for managing employee benefits. It simplified HR processes for small and medium-sized businesses and experienced rapid growth.\n\n3. **Instacart** - Instacart revolutionized grocery shopping by offering same-day delivery from local stores. Its user-friendly app and efficient service disrupted traditional grocery delivery methods.\n\n4. **Wealthfront** - As a robo-advisor, Wealthfront automated investment services, making wealth management accessible to a broader audience through algorithmic portfolio management.\n\n5. **ClassPass** - ClassPass introduced a subscription model that gave members access to a variety of fitness classes at different studios, offering flexibility and variety for fitness enthusiasts.\n\n6. **Zendesk** - Zendesk provided customer service and support software that could be integrated into a company's website. It helped businesses improve customer communication and satisfaction.\n\n7. **Oscar Health** - Oscar Health entered the health insurance market with a tech-driven approach, focusing on a user-friendly experience and transparency in healthcare coverage.\n\n8. **Stripe** - Stripe made it easier for businesses to accept payments online. Its developer-friendly platform streamlined the transaction process for countless online merchants and services.\n\n9. **Dollar Shave Club** - This direct-to-consumer razor and personal grooming company gained fame with its viral marketing campaign and subscription-based business model, challenging established razor manufacturers.\n\n10. **Pinterest** - While Pinterest was founded earlier, it was in 2014 that it started to gain significant traction as a social media platform for discovering and sharing creative ideas.\n\nThese startups are notable for their innovative approaches to their respective markets, and many have since become household names or have significantly influenced their industries. While some of these companies have grown into large corporations or have been acquired by even larger ones, they all started with a vision to solve a particular problem or fill a gap in the market in 2014 or shortly before.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
